05199nam a22006495i 9780226351261DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20102010ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802263512617 a10.7208/97802263512612doi  a(DE-B1597)524194  a(OCoLC)664565683  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aJZ5548b.S874 2010eb 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a303.6/622200aStrengthening Peace in Post-Civil War States :bTransforming Spoilers into Stakeholders /ced. by Caroline A. Hartzell, Matthew Hoddie. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b1 line drawing, 1 table, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tONE. Introduction -- tPART ONE. Restructuring Institutions -- tTWO. Building Legitimate States after Civil Wars -- tTHREE. States and Civil Societies following Civil Wars -- tFOUR. Electoral Rules and Post–Civil War Conflict Management: The Limitations of Institutional Design -- tFIVE. Sustaining Peace: Renegotiating Postwar Settlements -- tPART TWO. Soft Intervention -- tSIX. Soft Intervention in Africa: US Efforts to Generate Support for Peace -- tSEVEN. Soft Intervention and the Transformation of Militias into Political Parties -- tEIGHT. Cautionary Tales: Soft Intervention and Civil Society -- tNINE. Soft Intervention and the Puzzling Neglect of Economic Actors -- tTEN. Conclusions -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmong the more frequent and most devastating of conflicts, civil wars—from Yugoslavia to Congo—frequently reignite and even spill over into the international sphere. Given the inherent fragility of civil war peace agreements, innovative approaches must be taken to ensure the successful resolution of these conflicts. Strengthening Peace in Post­–Civil War States provides both analytical frameworks and a series of critical case studies demonstrating the effectiveness of a range of strategies for keeping the peace. Coeditors Matthew Hoddie and Caroline A. Hartzell here contend that lasting peace relies on aligning the self-interest of individuals and communities with the society-wide goal of ending war; if citizens and groups have a stake in peace, they will seek to maintain and defend it. The rest of the contributors explore two complementary approaches toward achieving this goal: restructuring domestic institutions and soft intervention. Some essays examine the first tactic, which involves reforming governments that failed to prevent war, while others discuss the second, an umbrella term for a number of non-military strategies for outside actors to assist in keeping the peace.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCivil war. 0aPeace-building. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aEmmanuel, Nikolas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoley, Michael W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHartzell, Caroline A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHartzell, Caroline A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHoddie, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoddie, Matthew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLake, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLyons, Terrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMozaffar, Shaheen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoeder, Philip G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRothchild, Donald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r